metadata.name: tratti #177
metadata.description:
"tratti" is an Italian word that has many different meanings. When we started working on this piece, we wanted to create something that combines our traits ("tratti" in Italian).
We had this urge to channel the turbulent times we're living in now into this artwork using just lines ("tratti" in Italian).

We don't know what to do now, we're here, and that's all that matters. We're here for our families, our friends, and our community. Like everything in life, there are joyful times and challenging times. We must accept happiness as something that is not constant but that we feel at times (a "tratti" in Italian).

With "tratti", we want to send a message to every disheartened human being: "Stay strong and never let anyone or anything crush the hope in you. Joyful times are around the corner".

metadata.name: The City #253
metadata.description:
// The City //

Cities are the most complex human-made interventions on Earth. The human settlements are growing like huge organisms ‚Äì and the growth is often impossible to plan, control or limit.
Cities as a phenomenon are with their incredible complexity highly enigmatic structures, that are as fascinating as they are terrifying.

This project is a study of the beauty of complexity.

Each city iteration is an entirely unique structure with unique hatching, arrangement of buildings, heights, sizes, additions and rare items.
The cities are made even more organic by the meticulous modelling of analog ink drawing.

The project is 100% generative. All lines, hatching and dots are generated for each iteration.

As a gesture of appreciation towards our supporters, 20% of royalties will go to the original minter.

Key commands:
Press 's' to save a png version
Press '2' to render at twice the resolution
Press 'b' to remove the colored background before saving

The loading progress is animated, hence the epileptic trigger warning.
Due to memory constraints on mobile devices, rendering uses a lower resolution on these.
-----------

Original concept by @Lax_raven
All code by @r1b2art

metadata.name: Absorbed #106
metadata.description:
A collaboration between leading British high-end audio brand KEF, generative artist hieroglyphica, and creative studio Parameta, Absorbed embodies the process of noise becoming high-fidelity sound through KEF‚Äôs Metamaterial Absorption Technology (MAT‚Ñ¢). 

MAT‚Ñ¢ makes the KEF sound what it is: absorbing unwanted distortion to deliver pure, accurate sound exactly as the artist intended. Inspired by this intricacy, Absorbed illustrates pseudorandom networks of patterns, slowly emerging and transforming into the maze-like form of MAT‚Ñ¢. Clarity is revealed, noise is absorbed ‚Äì high-fidelity is found.

The noise fields used in Absorbed are of two distinct types: conventional gradient noise and ‚Äúsinusoidal‚Äù noise, an original algorithm developed for this series. The use of animation as artistic medium reflects the artists‚Äô belief that no single frame can capture the full range of complexity found in the tension between sound and noise, and lets collectors observe for themselves this ever-shifting dialogue. A more extensive discussion of the algorithms used in Absorbed can be found in hieroglyphica‚Äôs companion article on fx(text).

- spacebar will pause and resume the animation
- s will save a still image of the current frame
- technically minded collectors can consult the index.html file for info on how to render and save high-resolution images
- use of hardware acceleration in Chrome may impact performance

Founded by BBC engineer Raymond Cooke in 1961, KEF is a leading British innovator of high-end audio products including HiFi speakers, subwoofers, architectural speakers, wireless speaker-systems, and headphones. Find out more at kef.com or visit our Discord at discord.com/invite/u48Z9yjY2q.

metadata.name: Sixty# #214
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe there‚Äôs room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Sa·πÖkhƒÅra #56
metadata.description:
üéß CLICK/TAP FOR SOUND ON

Sa·πÖkhƒÅra is a portrait of symbolic consciousness in three movements.

Colorful automata represents direct experience: touch, sight, hearing, smell, taste and thought in a ceaseless flow of novelty.

The automata congeals into form alluding to the way our minds close over experience with symbolic representation, like a plastic bag coming down over a kaleidoscope of butterflies. What was free in the open air is now trapped. What was previously wild and unpredictable is now under control, frozen and communicable.

The form‚Äôs dispersal mimics the release of mental formation, the unbinding of a symbol, the letting go of a belief. It‚Äôs a visceral reflection of the process of ceasing to identify with separateness. To strain the previous metaphor, it‚Äôs the opening of the bag and letting the butterflies return to the flow of raw, boundless experience.

‚Äî

K.C. Austin
From his cockpit in the Blue Ridge Mountains K.C. Austin (aka bzor) spends his days shaping realtime software art systems of all stripes. Informed by game design, modular synths, virtual reality and consciousness research, K.C. plays shaders like a fiddle and fashions creative pipelines like a spider spins webs.

James Paterson
Fascinated by the relationship between ancient and futuristic mediums, James Paterson has been exploring a unique synthesis of drawing, code, animation and sculpture under the moniker ‚ÄòPresstube‚Äô since 1999. Paterson draws inspiration from meditation, molecular biology, music, parenting and psychedelics - the seen, the heard, the felt, the cognized.
